One of the very nice things about SPICE is that both input and output formats are plain-text, which is the most universal and easy-to-edit electronic format around.  Practically \textit{any} computer will be able to edit and display this format, even if the SPICE program itself is not resident on that computer.  If the user desires, he or she is free to use the advanced capabilities of word processing programs to make the output look fancier.  Comments can even be inserted between lines of the output for further clarity to the reader.
 



\section{ The command-line interface}
 

If you've used DOS or UNIX operating systems before in a command-line shell environment, you may wonder why we have to use the "$<$" symbol between the word "spice" and the name of the netlist file to be interpreted.  Why not just enter the file name as the first argument to the command "spice" as we do when we invoke the text editor?  The answer is that SPICE has the option of an \textit{interactive} mode, whereby each line of the netlist can be interpreted as it is entered through the computer's Standard Input (stdin).  If you simple type "spice" at the prompt and press \textbf{[Enter]}, SPICE will begin to interpret anything you type in to it (live).
 

 

For most applications, its nice to save your netlist work in a separate file and then let SPICE interpret that file when you're ready.  This is the way I encourage SPICE to be used, and so this is the way its presented in this lesson.  In order to use SPICE this way in a command-line environment, we need to use the "$<$" redirection symbol to direct the contents of your netlist file to Standard Input (stdin), which SPICE can then process.
 



\section{ Circuit components}
 

Remember that this tutorial is not exhaustive by any means, and that all descriptions for elements in the SPICE language are documented here in condensed form.  SPICE is a very capable piece of software with lots of options, and I'm only going to document a few of them.
 

 

\textit{All} components in a SPICE source file are primarily identified by the first letter in each respective line.  Characters following the identifying letter are used to distinguish one component of a certain type from another of the same type (r1, r2, r3, rload, rpullup, etc.), and need not follow any particular naming convention, so long as no more than eight characters are used in both the component identifying letter and the distinguishing name. 
 

\index{Component names, SPICE}
 

For example, suppose you were simulating a digital circuit with "pullup" and "pulldown" resistors.  The name \texttt{rpullup} would be valid because it is seven characters long.  The name \texttt{rpulldown}, however, is nine characters long.  This may cause problems when SPICE interprets the netlist.
 

 

You can actually get away with component names in excess of eight total characters if there are no other similarly-named components in the source file.  SPICE only pays attention to the first eight characters of the first field in each line, so \texttt{rpulldown} is actually interpreted as \texttt{rpulldow} with the "n" at the end being ignored.  Therefore, any other resistor having the first eight characters in its first field will be seen by SPICE as the same resistor, defined twice, which will cause an error (i.e. \texttt{rpulldown1} and \texttt{rpulldown2} would be interpreted as the same name, \texttt{rpulldow}).
 

 

It should also be noted that SPICE ignores character case, so \texttt{r1} and \texttt{R1} are interpreted by SPICE as one and the same.
 

 

SPICE allows the use of metric prefixes in specifying component values, which is a very handy feature.  However, the prefix convention used by SPICE differs somewhat from standard metric symbols, primarily due to the fact that netlists are restricted to standard ASCII characters (ruling out Greek letters such as $\mu$ for the prefix "micro") and that SPICE is case-insensitive, so "m" (which is the standard symbol for "milli") and "M" (which is the standard symbol for "Mega") are interpreted identically.  Here are a few examples of prefixes used in SPICE netlists:
 

\index{Metric prefixes, SPICE}
\bigskip 
 

\texttt{r1 1 0 2t} (Resistor R$_{1}$, 2t = 2 Tera-ohms = 2 T$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r2 1 0 4g} (Resistor R$_{2}$, 4g = 4 Giga-ohms = 4 G$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r3 1 0 47meg} (Resistor R$_{3}$, 47meg = 47 Mega-ohms = 47 M$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r4 1 0 3.3k} (Resistor R$_{4}$, 3.3k = 3.3 kilo-ohms = 3.3 k$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r5 1 0 55m} (Resistor R$_{5}$, 55m = 55 milli-ohms = 55 m$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r6 1 0 10u} (Resistor R$_{6}$, 10u = 10 micro-ohms 10 $\mu$$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r7 1 0 30n} (Resistor R$_{7}$, 30n = 30 nano-ohms = 30 n$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r8 1 0 5p} (Resistor R$_{8}$, 5p = 5 pico-ohms = 5 p$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r9 1 0 250f} (Resistor R$_{9}$, 250f = 250 femto-ohms = 250 f$\Omega$)
 

\bigskip 
\index{Scientific notation, SPICE}
 

Scientific notation is also allowed in specifying component values.  For example:
 

\bigskip 
 

\texttt{r10 1 0 4.7e3} (Resistor R$_{10}$, 4.7e3 = 4.7 x 10$^{3}$ ohms = 4.7 kilo-ohms = 4.7 k$\Omega$)
 

 

\texttt{r11 1 0 1e-12} (Resistor R$_{11}$, 1e-12 = 1 x 10$^{-12}$ ohms = 1 pico-ohm = 1 p$\Omega$)
 

\bigskip 
 

The unit (ohms, volts, farads, henrys, etc.) is automatically determined by the type of component being specified.  SPICE "knows" that all of the above examples are "ohms" because they are all resistors (r1, r2, r3, . . . ).  If they were capacitors, the values would be interpreted as "farads," if inductors, then "henrys," etc.
 


\subsection{ Passive components}

\subsubsection{ CAPACITORS}
\index{Capacitors, SPICE}
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  c[name] [node1] [node2] [value] ic=[initial voltage]
Example 1:     c1 12 33 10u 
Example 2:     c1 12 33 10u ic=3.5
~
\endgroup 
 

\textbf{Comments:}  The "initial condition" (\texttt{ic=}) variable is the capacitor's voltage in units of \textit{volts} at the start of DC analysis.  It is an optional value, with the starting voltage assumed to be zero if unspecified.  Starting current values for capacitors are interpreted by SPICE only if the \texttt{.tran} analysis option is invoked (with the "\texttt{uic}" option). 
 



\subsubsection{ INDUCTORS}
\index{Inductors, SPICE}
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  l[name] [node1] [node2] [value] ic=[initial current]
Example 1:     l1 12 33 133m 
Example 2:     l1 12 33 133m ic=12.7m
~
\endgroup 
 

\textbf{Comments:}  The "initial condition" (\texttt{ic=}) variable is the inductor's current in units of \textit{amps} at the start of DC analysis.  It is an optional value, with the starting current assumed to be zero if unspecified.  Starting current values for inductors are interpreted by SPICE only if the .tran analysis option is invoked.  
 



\subsubsection{ INDUCTOR COUPLING (transformers)}
\index{Mutual inductance, SPICE}
\index{Transformers, SPICE}
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  k[name] l[name] l[name] [coupling factor]
Example 1:     k1 l1 l2 0.999
~
\endgroup 
 

\textbf{Comments:}  SPICE will only allow coupling factor values between 0 and 1 (non-inclusive), with 0 representing no coupling and 1 representing perfect coupling.  The order of specifying coupled inductors (l1, l2 or l2, l1) is irrelevant.
 



\subsubsection{ RESISTORS}
\index{Resistors, SPICE}
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  r[name] [node1] [node2] [value]
Example:       rload 23 15 3.3k
~
\endgroup 
 

\textbf{Comments:} In case you were wondering, there is no declaration of resistor power dissipation rating in SPICE.  All components are assumed to be indestructible.  If only real life were this forgiving!
 




\subsection{ Active components}
\index{Model, SPICE}
\index{Semiconductor model, SPICE}
 

All semiconductor components must have their electrical characteristics described in a line starting with the word "\texttt{.model}", which tells SPICE exactly how the device will behave.  Whatever parameters are not explicitly defined in the \texttt{.model} card will default to values pre-programmed in SPICE.  However, the \texttt{.model} card \textit{must} be included, and at least specify the model name and device type (d, npn, pnp, njf, pjf, nmos, or pmos).
 


\subsubsection{ DIODES}
\index{Diodes, SPICE}
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  d[name] [anode] [cathode] [model]
Example:       d1 1 2 mod1
~
\endgroup 
 

\textbf{DIODE MODELS:}
 

\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  .model [modelname] d [parmtr1=x] [parmtr2=x] . . .
Example:       .model mod1 d
Example:       .model mod2 d vj=0.65 rs=1.3
~
\endgroup 
<hypertarget>diodeparameter</hypertarget>
 

\textit{Parameter definitions:}
 

 

\texttt{is} = saturation current in amps
 

 

\texttt{rs} = junction resistance in ohms
 

 

\texttt{n} = emission coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{tt} = transit time in seconds
 

 

\texttt{cjo} = zero-bias junction capacitance in farads
 

 

\texttt{vj} = junction potential in volts
 

 

\texttt{m} = grading coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{eg} = activation energy in electron-volts
 

 

\texttt{xti} = saturation-current temperature exponent (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{kf} = flicker noise coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{af} = flicker noise exponent (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{fc} = forward-bias depletion capacitance coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{bv} = reverse breakdown voltage in volts
 

 

\texttt{ibv} = current at breakdown voltage in amps
 

\bigskip 
 

\textbf{Comments:}  The model name \textit{must} begin with a letter, not a number.  If you plan to specify a model for a 1N4003 rectifying diode, for instance, you cannot use "1n4003" for the model name.  An alternative might be "m1n4003" instead.
 



\subsubsection{ TRANSISTORS, bipolar junction -- BJT}
\index{Transistors, bipolar, SPICE}
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  q[name] [collector] [base] [emitter] [model]
Example:       q1 2 3 0 mod1
~
\endgroup 
 

\textbf{BJT TRANSISTOR MODELS:}
 

\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
General form:  .model [modelname] [npn or pnp] [parmtr1=x] . . .
Example:       .model mod1 pnp
Example:       .model mod2 npn bf=75 is=1e-14
~
\endgroup 
 

The model examples shown above are very nonspecific.  To accurately model real-life transistors, more parameters are necessary.  Take these two examples, for the popular 2N2222 and 2N2907 transistors (the "\texttt{+}") characters represent line-continuation marks in SPICE, when you wish to break a single line (card) into two or more separate lines on your text editor:
 

\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
~
Example:       .model m2n2222 npn is=19f bf=150 vaf=100 ikf=.18
+                     ise=50p ne=2.5 br=7.5 var=6.4 ikr=12m
+                     isc=8.7p nc=1.2 rb=50 re=0.4 rc=0.4 cje=26p
+                     tf=0.5n cjc=11p tr=7n xtb=1.5 kf=0.032f af=1
~
\endgroup 
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
Example:       .model m2n2907 pnp is=1.1p bf=200 nf=1.2 vaf=50 
+                     ikf=0.1 ise=13p ne=1.9 br=6 rc=0.6 cje=23p
+                     vje=0.85 mje=1.25 tf=0.5n cjc=19p vjc=0.5
+                     mjc=0.2 tr=34n xtb=1.5
~
\endgroup 
 

\textit{Parameter definitions:}
 

 

\texttt{is} = transport saturation current in amps
 

 

\texttt{bf} = ideal maximum forward Beta (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{nf} = forward current emission coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{vaf} = forward Early voltage in volts
 

 

\texttt{ikf} = corner for forward Beta high-current rolloff in amps
 

 

\texttt{ise} = B-E leakage saturation current in amps
 

 

\texttt{ne} = B-E leakage emission coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{br} = ideal maximum reverse Beta (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{nr} = reverse current emission coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{bar} = reverse Early voltage in volts
 

 

\texttt{ikr}ikr = corner for reverse Beta high-current rolloff in amps
 

 

\texttt{isc}isc = B-C leakage saturation current in amps
 

 

\texttt{nc} = B-C leakage emission coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{rb} = zero bias base resistance in ohms
 

 

\texttt{irb} = current for base resistance halfway value in amps
 

 

\texttt{rbm} = minimum base resistance at high currents in ohms
 

 

\texttt{re} = emitter resistance in ohms
 

 

\texttt{rc} = collector resistance in ohms
 

 

\texttt{cje} = B-E zero-bias depletion capacitance in farads
 

 

\texttt{vje} = B-E built-in potential in volts
 

 

\texttt{mje} = B-E junction exponential factor (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{tf} = ideal forward transit time (seconds)
 

 

\texttt{xtf} = coefficient for bias dependence of transit time (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{vtf} = B-C voltage dependence on transit time, in volts
 

 

\texttt{itf} = high-current parameter effect on transit time, in amps
 

 

\texttt{ptf} = excess phase at f=1/(transit time)(2)(pi) Hz, in degrees
 

 

\texttt{cjc} = B-C zero-bias depletion capacitance in farads
 

 

\texttt{vjc} = B-C built-in potential in volts
 

 

\texttt{mjc} = B-C junction exponential factor (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{xjcj} = B-C depletion capacitance fraction connected in base node (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{tr} = ideal reverse transit time in seconds
 

 

\texttt{cjs} = zero-bias collector-substrate capacitance in farads
 

 

\texttt{vjs} = substrate junction built-in potential in volts
 

 

\texttt{mjs} = substrate junction exponential factor (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{xtb} = forward/reverse Beta temperature exponent
 

 

\texttt{eg} = energy gap for temperature effect on transport saturation current in electron-volts
 

 

\texttt{xti} = temperature exponent for effect on transport saturation current (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{kf} = flicker noise coefficient (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{af} = flicker noise exponent (unitless)
 

 

\texttt{fc} = forward-bias depletion capacitance formula coefficient (unitless)
 

\bigskip 
 

\textbf{Comments:}  Just as with diodes, the model name given for a particular transistor type \textit{must} begin with a letter, not a number.  That's why the examples given above for the 2N2222 and 2N2907 types of BJTs are named "m2n2222" and "q2n2907" respectively.
 

 

As you can see, SPICE allows for very detailed specification of transistor properties.  Many of the properties listed above are well beyond the scope and interest of the beginning electronics student, and aren't even useful apart from knowing the equations SPICE uses to model BJT transistors.  For those interested in learning more about transistor modeling in SPICE, consult other books, such as Andrei Vladimirescu's \textit{The Spice Book} (ISBN 0-471-60926-9).
 



