\subsection{ Multiple-source AC network}
 
\medskip \centerline{\includegraphics{01023.eps}} 
 

One of the idiosyncrasies of SPICE is its inability to handle any loop in a circuit exclusively composed of series voltage sources and inductors.  Therefore, the "loop" of V$_{1}$-L$_{1}$-L$_{2}$-V$_{2}$-V$_{1}$ is unacceptable.  To get around this, I had to insert a \textit{low}-resistance resistor somewhere in that loop to break it up.  Thus, we have R$_{bogus}$ between 3 and 4 (with 1 pico-ohm of resistance), and V$_{2}$ between 4 and 0.  The circuit above is the original design, while the circuit below has R$_{bogus}$ inserted to avoid the SPICE error.  
 

 
